{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17477163","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17477163"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:58:49+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:58:49+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14222"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14222","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14222"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.13,0.06,0.35,0.36,0.1]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6909"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112531"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6909","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6909"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14222"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94565"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"38"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1804"},{"type":"tags","id":"2187"},{"type":"tags","id":"4988"},{"type":"tags","id":"4991"},{"type":"tags","id":"5326"},{"type":"tags","id":"5351"},{"type":"tags","id":"5438"},{"type":"tags","id":"5448"},{"type":"tags","id":"11622"},{"type":"tags","id":"11640"},{"type":"tags","id":"12731"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"15827"},{"type":"contributions","id":"32915"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40063"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44205"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44991"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45198"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45420"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45426"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112531","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/112531"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old Aboriginal woman presents to the General Practice clinic with her 6-month-old son for a routine check-up and vaccinations. The woman is from a remote community in the Northern Territory. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. Her son has been developing normally and she has no concerns about his health. He has no significant medical history and was born at 37 weeks gestation. On examination, the child appears well with vital signs within normal limits.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe mother asks about the recommended vaccination schedule for her child, as she has heard it might be different for Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander children.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes how the current Australian Immunisation Schedule recommendations for Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander children at six months age differs from the general population?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Additional Pneumococcal vaccine dose","Additional Pneumococcal and Hepatitis A vaccine doses","Additional Pneumococcal, Hepatitis A, and Meningococcal B vaccine doses","Additional Pneumococcal, Hepatitis A, Meningococcal B, and annual influenza vaccines","Same schedule as non-Indigenous children with earlier commencement"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe current Australian Immunisation Schedule recommends an \u003Cstrong\u003Eadditional pneumococcal \u003C/strong\u003Evaccine at six months age for for Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander children.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe enhanced schedule for Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander children reflects a higher risk of certain infectious diseases in Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander populations, particularly in certain geographical areas. The recommended additional vaccines for Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander children include:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPneumococcal vaccine: Additional doses at six months and four years (only Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander children in WA, NT, SA, Qld who have not received Prevenar 20 previously)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHepatitis A vaccine: At 18 months and four years of age\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMeningococcal B vaccine: At 2, 4, and 12 months of age\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInfluenza vaccine: Recommended for all indigenous children annually from 6 months of age (noting the annual flu vaccine is recommended for all children between six months and five years age also).\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe following answer options are incorrect as they contain recommended vaccines for ages other than six months:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAdditional Pneumococcal and Hepatitis A vaccine doses\u003C/strong\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAdditional Pneumococcal, Hepatitis A, and Meningococcal B vaccine doses\u003C/strong\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAdditional Pneumococcal, Hepatitis A, Meningococcal B vaccine doses and annual influenza vaccines\u003C/strong\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUsing the\u003Cstrong\u003E same schedule as non-Indigenous children with earlier commencement\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect. The schedule doesn\u0027t start earlier, but includes additional vaccines and doses.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThese enhanced schedules for Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander children are crucial in protecting this vulnerable population from various infectious diseases. The introduction of these additional vaccines has helped reduce the incidence of these diseases, but maintaining high vaccination coverage, especially in high-risk populations, remains important for continued protection.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHealthcare providers should be aware of these recommendations and ensure that Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander children are offered all recommended vaccines according to the schedule. It\u0027s also important to provide culturally appropriate education to parents about the importance of these additional vaccines.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander children are recommended to receive additional doses of Pneumococcal vaccine at 6 months and 4 years (only Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander children in WA, NT, SA, Qld who have not received Prevenar 20 previously)"],"references":["Australian Government Department of Health. National Immunisation Program Schedule. Canberra: Australian Government Department of Health; 2023. Available from: https://www.health.gov.au/topics/immunisation/when-to-get-vaccinated/national-immunisation-program-schedule.","2025 influenza vaccination program: advice for health professionals. In: Australian Government Department of Health and Aged Care [online]. Accessed 2025 Jun 25. Available at: https://www.health.gov.au/sites/default/files/2025-03/2025-influenza-vaccination-program-advice-for-health-professionals_0.pdf","Gilsdorf JR. Hib Vaccines: Their Impact on Haemophilus influenzae Type b Disease. J Infect Dis. 2021 Sep 30;224(12 Suppl 2):S321-S330. doi: 10.1093/infdis/jiaa537. PMID: 34590133; PMCID: PMC8482018."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94565"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14222"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94565","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/94565"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-02T13:13:49+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-02T13:14:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6909"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevi